[Student "S"]
{With 19 points you are too strong to open 1NT so you open 1\D. Partner responds 2\D.  

Perhaps you can make 5\D. But 9 tricks are easier than 11  so you bid 3NT. Notice that there was no reason to "show" your \S suit. If partner held 4 \Ss he would not have bid 2\D. 

East plays 3NT. South leads the \HQ.

<b>East plays 3NT. South leads the \HQ.</b>

Winners: \S 1 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 3 : Total = 7

You can create one winner in \Ds if they split 3-2, but too late, the defense would have set up their \Hs. So you must get 2 more \S tricks.

This is one of the most misplayed positions in bridge. The usual approach is to lead the \SQ, hoping that South holds the \SK. But this can't succeed. If South does hold the \SK he will cover, either this trick or the \SJ, and someone's \ST will become a winner. Of course if North has the \SK then the finesse will fail, along with your chance of 2 more winners.

The correct way to play for 2 more tricks is to hope <b>NORTH</b> has the \SK and lead twice toward your \S Q J. So win the first trick, play \S4 to dummy's \SA. Lead the \S3 toward your hand, playing the \SJ if North plays low. (Of course if North ever plays the \SK he gives you two winners immediately.) When the \SJ wins, return to dummy with the \DA and lead the \S6 toward your \SQ.

When North holds the \SK you can always get 3 \S tricks if you play correctly. }
[Play "W"]HQ

